<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The troubled lender Banco EspÃ­rito Santo will be shut down, and its healthy businesses transferred to a new bank, as part of 4.9 billion euro rescue plan financed primarily by the Portuguese government, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/04/business/international/banco-espirito-santo-of-portugal-appears-headed-for-a-bailout.html">Jack Ewing and Chad Bray write in The New York Times</a></b>. In a plan announced on Monday, the Portuguese government will provide most of the money for the rescue in the form of a loan, but the heaviest losses will be absorbed by Banco EspÃ­rito Santo shareholders and some creditors.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe plan will serve as an early test of new European rules intended to make sure that investors, and not just taxpayers, most directly deal with the fallout when banks fail,â Mr. Ewing and Mr. Bray write. Though the bank is nowhere near large enough to rank among the eurozoneâs biggest banks, <b>the rescue will still be costly</b> for a country that emerged from an international bailout only months ago. Problems at Banco EspÃ­rito Santo also raise questions about what other troubles may still lurk in the European banking system.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Monday, the Bank of Portugal portrayed the rescue as being paid for by the countryâs bank resolution fund, which is bankrolled by financial institutions. But <b>the government will loan the fund â¬4.4 billion</b> of the â¬4.9 billion cost of the bailout. The new bank will eventually be sold in an attempt to recover the taxpayer loan. As part of the rescue plan, the bankâs sound assets â including deposits and loans that are likely to be repaid â will be moved into a so-called bridge bank to be renamed Novo Banco. <b>The bankâs problem assets will remain with the existing bank</b>, which will be shut down over time.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">TALKS ON ARGENTINAâS DEFAULT DRAG ON <span class="divider"> | </span></span> A lawyer for Argentina told a federal judge on Friday that the nation had lost faith in the mediator appointed to work with a group of hedge funds that hold the countryâs bonds, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/08/01/u-s-judge-rejects-argentinas-appeal-for-new-mediator">DealBookâs Alexandra Stevenson writes</a></b>. But the judge, Thomas P. Griesa of Federal District Court in Manhattan, rejected the request and said talks would have to continue. Argentina defaulted on Wednesday for the second time in 13 years after last-minute talks broke down and the nation missed a regular bond payment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The lawyer, Jonathan Blackman, pointed to a statement issued by the mediator, Daniel Pollack, on Wednesday that said Argentina was in âimminent default.â That statement was â<b>harmful and prejudicial</b>,â Mr. Blackman said, and asked that Mr. Pollack be replaced. Mr. Blackman also said Mr. Pollackâs statement had caused Argentina âdeep concern.â Judge Griesa, who appointed Mr. Pollack to help mediate the last-ditch talks, <b>emphasized the importance of continuing the mediated talks</b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Also on Friday, the International Swaps and Derivatives Association said Argentinaâs failure to make a payment on its bonds would activate credit default swaps on the countryâs debt, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/08/01/argentina-default-is-ruled-a-credit-event-for-swaps">Peter Eavis writes in DealBook</a></b>. In the coming days, investors who used the swaps to insure against the default will collect money from investors on the other side of the trade.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">BIG BANKS STILL A RISK <span class="divider"> | </span></span> A new study that assessed the value to banks of the implied guarantee by taxpayers raised more questions than it answered, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/08/03/business/big-banks-still-a-risk.html">Gretchen Morgenson writes in the Fair Game column</a></b>. The study, released last week, was requested by two senators â Sherrod Brown, a Democrat from Ohio, and David Vitter, a Louisiana Republican â who wrote a bill last year that would require big banks to set aside significantly more capital to protect against losses. Mr. Brown also sponsored a hearing on Thursday to discuss the Government Accountability Office findings.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The discussion went beyond the report and explored the current state of banking, the limits of the Dodd-Frank Act and what should be done about banks that are simply too big to manage. âCentral to the hearing is that six years after the financial crisis, itâs clear that <b>some institutions remain too complex and interconnected to be unwound quickly</b> and efficiently if they get into trouble,â Ms. Morgenson writes. âStated simply, there is an enormous value in a bankâs ability to <b>tap the taxpayer for a bailout</b> rather than being forced to go through bankruptcy.â She adds, âThat value was what the G.A.O. had been asked to measure. But its methodology was convoluted and its conclusions hardly definitive.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Data on <b>consumer spending</b> is out at 8:30 a.m. The <b>American International Group</b> reports second-quarter earnings after the market closes.</p>
